	abstract = {Here is a draft abstract comparing convolutional neural networks (CNNs) and Bayesian neural networks (BNNs) for modeling uncertainty in neural networks: Neural networks have become a popular and powerful tool for many machine learning tasks. However, standard neural networks tend to produce overconfident predictions and do not properly model uncertainty. This is concerning in applications such as medical diagnosis or autonomous driving where assessing model confidence is crucial. Two approaches to address this limitation are Bayesian neural networks (BNNs) and ensemble methods such as convolutional neural networks (CNNs). BNNs place prior probability distributions over model weights and use Bayes' rule for inference. This allows BNNs to represent both epistemic uncertainty and aleatoric noise. Meanwhile, CNN ensembles train multiple models on different subsets of the data and aggregate their predictions. This captures more realistic variance across the ensemble. In this work, we evaluate and compare these two approaches for modeling uncertainty on image classification tasks. Our experiments show that BNNs can better capture epistemic uncertainty due to limited data; Predictions are aggregated across the ensemble, capturing variance due to data subsampling. While CNN ensembles do not explicitly model epistemic uncertainty, the variance between models increases with greater model capacity and smaller datasets, partially capturing this effect. Ensembles are computationally expensive, requiring training multiple models.  © 2023 IEEE.},
	type = {Conference paper},
	publication_stage = {Final},
	source = {Scopus},
	note = {Cited by: 0}
}

