	abstract = {We have reviewed some of the progress and problems in the general area of computer applications to medical diagnosis. Three main reasons to use computers as aids to diagnosis were discussed: (1) to reduce errors; (2) to provide economy and efficiency; and (3) to provide quantitative measures of probability based on collective past experience. We have discussed the general Bayesian model for medical diagnosis and indicated that the development of a useful mathematical model for medical diagnosis is not a trivial problem, either medically or mathematically, with much collaborative work remaining to be done. We have given an outline for evaluating mathematical models for diagnosis, imposing statistical rigor in evaluation of results, and have suggested those steps which appear to be most important in bringing the retrieval and computational powers of the computer into the practice of medicine. Already the impact of the computer has been felt in medicine, stimulating physicians to attempt to be more rigorous in defining concepts, in collecting information, and in making well-founded decisions. Much work remains to be done in this still-new and challenging area. © 1966 Association for Computing Machinery, Inc. All rights reserved.},
